{
  "text": "Regardless of its labelling by esteemed societies or its scientific merits, the question remains whether classifying obesity as a disease is beneficial for patients. There is a strong argument that disease-status would provide a mandate for governments to take obesity more seriously, and to provide more funding for obesity-related treatment strategies such as metabolic surgery [CITATION_1] . This is particularly apt in the UK, where provision of metabolic surgery for morbidly obese patients per capita is among the worst in the whole of Western Europe [CITATION_2] : a shameful indictment which is simply unacceptable and cannot be justified. Furthermore, labelling obesity as a disease may raise its profile among charitable societies, and promote more funding for research into the prevention and effective management of obesity.",
